{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-topic-topic-tsx","path":"/topics/alopecia-areata/","result":{"data":{"firstChapter":{"id":"6e5fa7b5-85f4-59b0-b6d5-af565dbeca62","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[],"depth":1,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 9c999333-85ec-4e6b-9306-73abed5aa500 --><h1>Alopecia areata: Summary</h1><!-- end field 9c999333-85ec-4e6b-9306-73abed5aa500 -->","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 4b851b4a-121e-4564-bb3f-9b718381376d --><!-- begin field 9f08ffb8-e424-4bce-ae0f-963a250d0efe --><ul><li>Alopecia areata is a chronic, inflammatory condition affecting the hair follicles which leads to sudden onset of non-scarring alopecia (hair loss where the hair follicles are generally preserved).<ul><li>Any hair-bearing skin can be involved, but it most commonly affects the scalp or beard and, less frequently, the eyebrows and eyelashes.</li><li>Total loss of scalp hair (alopecia totalis) or scalp and body hair (alopecia universalis) is rare.</li><li>Nail changes are seen in 10–15% of people.</li></ul></li><li>Alopecia areata occurs when hairs are prematurely converted from the growth (anagen) to the loss (telogen) phase, but the exact cause is unknown.</li><li>Alopecia areata is a relatively common condition and is estimated to affect 15 in 10,000 people in the UK.<ul><li>It can present at any age, and males and females are affected equally.</li></ul></li><li>The prognosis of alopecia areata is unpredictable.<ul><li>Spontaneous remission within one year may be seen in up to 80% of people with limited patches of hair loss of less than one year duration.</li></ul></li><li>A diagnosis of alopecia areata should be made on the basis of typical clinical features:<ul><li>Hair loss is usually patchy, producing circular or oval areas of loss. Diffuse hair loss is more unusual.</li><li>Exclamation mark hairs (short broken hairs which taper proximally) may be seen around the margin, or in any part of the patch, during active disease.</li></ul></li><li>Assessment of a person with suspected alopecia areata should include:<ul><li>How the hair loss is affecting them.</li><li>Any known trigger such as emotional or physical stress, their coping strategies and support network.</li><li>Any previous episodes of hair loss.</li><li>Any current or past treatments and their effectiveness.</li><li>Any family history of hair loss.</li><li>Any history or family history of associated atopy or autoimmune disease.</li><li>Examination of the skin for signs of scarring or inflammation which may suggest an alternative diagnosis.</li></ul></li><li>Management of alopecia areata should include advice on:<ul><li>The natural history of the condition and treatment options.</li><li>The option of no treatment if there is evidence of hair regrowth, or if there is no hair regrowth but less than 50% hair loss.</li><li>The option of a 3-month trial of potent or very potent topical corticosteroid treatment if there is no hair regrowth and more than 50% hair loss (or if treatment is preferred with less extensive involvement).</li><li>Cosmetic options to camouflage hair loss, such as hair extensions, dermatography (tattooing), and false eyelashes.</li><li>The option of using hairpieces and wigs if needed and appropriate.</li><li>The provision of psychological support if needed and appropriate.</li></ul></li><li>Referral to a paediatric dermatologist or dermatologist should be arranged (or specialist advice sought) if:<ul><li>Hair loss does not respond to treatment in primary care or if treatment is declined.</li><li>The diagnosis is uncertain.</li><li>A child, pregnant or breastfeeding woman is affected.</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 9f08ffb8-e424-4bce-ae0f-963a250d0efe --><!-- end item 4b851b4a-121e-4564-bb3f-9b718381376d -->","topic":{"id":"3f506159-b4f8-5d05-890d-a64054e84ccb","topicId":"2d81e675-d977-447f-ada9-76e40512ec53","topicName":"Alopecia areata","slug":"alopecia-areata","aliases":[],"chapters":[{"id":"6e5fa7b5-85f4-5